            <div type="general">
               <head>General</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Tillo is a large village in the province of Siirt about 8 km northeast of the town of Siirt in southeastern Turkey. Its name is probably derived from Arabic tall “hill, elevation” due to its location on the chain of hills surrounding the city of Siirt. As a consequence of the 1990 ban on non-Turkish names, Tillo was officially renamed Aydınlar.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Tillo is said to have been a relatively important centre of learning under the Ottomans and there are still several madrasas in the village. A number of Muslim saints are known to be buried in the village’s cemeteries, one of whom is the eminent Shaykh Ismaʕīl Faqīr Allāh b. Qāsim b. ʕAbd al-Jamāl (d. 1147/1734).</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">In the early 2000s, Lahdo (2009) estimated the number of Arabic-speaking inhabitants in Tillo as about 1,500; but their number seems to be decreasing rapidly.</p>
            </div>
